Discover 5 unique offline security tools

In this activity, I explored several offline security tools around the UWA campus. These tools are used to improve physical security and safety without relying on internet-based systems.

1. Security help point (emergency call station)  
I observed a security help point installed on campus. This device allows students to press a button to directly contact campus security in case of emergencies. It provides a fast and reliable way to request help.

2. CCTV camera  
I observed CCTV cameras installed in public areas. These cameras monitor activity and help deter suspicious behaviour. They can also provide recorded evidence if an incident happens.

3. Security patrol vehicle  
I observed a security patrol vehicle used by campus security staff. This allows security personnel to quickly move around campus and respond to incidents, improving overall safety.

4. Security presence (patrol system)  
I explored how security staff regularly patrol the campus. Even without digital systems, physical patrols act as a deterrent and allow immediate response to unusual situations. And will come to help people in need, contacting them via phone number or SafeZone app

5. Door peephole  
I observed a door peephole in my room at Unihall. This allows me to see who is outside the door before opening it, which helps prevent unauthorized access and improves personal safety.

Overall, these offline tools show that physical security measures are still very important in protecting people and maintaining safety in real environments.
